        "id": 1000411
      },
      "writtenOn": "2015-10-20T12:21:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I prefer not, we don\u0027t want to use this when generating shared libraries for example, otherwise each one of them is going to have its own copy of libstdc++ which can become rapidly problematic in the future.\n\nI\u0027m actually concerned about this use case, are we sure the DLLs will always link with the libstdc++ symbols in the executable that links them? It looks like a better solution would be to provide our own libstdc++ DLL so everything can link against the same, single, instance.",
      "parentUuid": "f91146d4_26e96fb1",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 100,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 100,
        "endChar": 23
      },
      "revId": "ea933342602505aafc2a7d5ec26ff078826b10a8",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "b9ec2e3d_b4c1568d",
        "filename": "Makefile.qemu1-common.mk",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 100,
      "author": {
        "id": 1079748
      },
      "writtenOn": "2015-10-20T17:40:15Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The last answer here suggests that statically linking a library into the exe, then loading a DLL that also references the same static lib might lead us into trouble:\nhttps://software.intel.com/en-us/forums/intel-visual-fortran-compiler-for-windows/topic/500949\n\nThe problem is that the DLL resolves _all symobls_ from the linked static lib at compile time. So, the exe and the static lib will end up with a different set of symbols from the same static lib, causing weird errors.",
      "parentUuid": "595172a7_ff82fbfe",
